n) Levels of risk associated with use of AI-enabled systems AI lifecycle phases Considerations in the Reliability and Fairness Audits of Predictive Models for Advance Care Planning [68] The article is about auditing two AI models currently deployed at Stanford Health Care: The Epic end-oflife (EOL) Index model (a model that predicts risk of 12-month mortality) and Stanford HM Advance Care Planning (ACP) model (a model that predicts risk of 3-12 month mortality) AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment Developing an Automated Assessment of In-session Patient Activation for Psychological Therapy: Codevelopment Approach [65] AutoCISC, the AI-enabled system developed in the study, uses ML techniques to automate the evaluation of patient activation in psychological therapy sessions by rating interactions based on the consultation interactions coding scheme (CICS), enabling more systematic and cost-effective assessments compared to traditional methods AI-assisted decision making High risk Development Engaging Multidisciplinary Clinical Users in the Design of an Artificial Intelligence-Powered Graphical User Interface for Intensive Care Unit Instability Decision Support [63] The study aims to develop a graphical user interface (GUI) for presenting an AIderived risk score in intensive care settings, engaging multidisciplinary clinicians through focus groups to ensure the GUI is transparent, interpretable, minimally disruptive, and supportive in decision-making AI-assisted decision making High risk Pre-development (POC) Ethical Considerations in Implementing AI for Mortality Prediction in the Emergency Department: Linking Theory and Practice [9] The study explores the ethical implications of using AI to predict patient mortality in emergency departments by engaging healthcare professionals in interviews, leading to the development of an ethical model that integrates six ethical principles (autonomy, beneficence, non-maleficence, justice, explicability, and professional governance) to guide AI implementation in healthcare settings AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment Title (alphabetically) High-level description of the AI-enabled systems or POC AI roles in the use case (See Table 6 for description) Levels of risk associated with use of AI-enabled systems AI lifecycle phases ProHealth eCoach: User-Centered Design and Development of an eCoach App to Promote Healthy Lifestyle with Personalized Activity Recommendations [57] This study describes the development of the Pro-Health eCoach system, an AI-driven tool designed to promote self-management featuring a mobile app that follows \"Google Material Design\" guidelines, wearable technology, and web content that not only offers personalised lifestyle recommendations but also visualises data and sets activity goals Emotional AI High risk Development Smartphone Applications for Triaging Adults with Skin Lesions that are Suspicious for Melanoma [71] The article assesses the accuracy of smartphone applications in diagnosing melanoma, finding that AI-based apps often miss melanomas, whereas apps that send images to dermatologists show potential but have high failure rates, highlighting the need for advancements in this rapidly evolving technology AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment The Application of the Principles of Responsible AI on Social Media Marketing for Digital Health [49] This study examines how AIpowered social media (i.e., Weibo, WeChat) enhances healthcare communication and marketing, analysing interviews with healthcare professionals to assess the impact of responsible AI practices, highlighting benefits and addressing ethical concerns to foster trust and privacy Human-controlled AI High risk Deployment The Participatory Value-Sensitive Design (VSD) of a mHealth App Targeting Citizens with Dementia in a Danish Municipality [38] The abstract describes the \"Sammen Om Demens\" project, where an AI-based smartphone app for dementia was developed using a participatory, Value-Sensitive Design process that resolved ethical dilemmas by incorporating diverse stakeholder values, resulting in an ethical, efficient, and democratic tool that aligns technological innovation with human values Human-controlled AI High risk Pre-development (POC) Title (alphabetically) High-level description of the AI-enabled systems or POC AI roles in the use case (See Table 6 for description) Levels of risk associated with use of AI-enabled systems AI lifecycle phases Utilization of Self-Diagnosis Health Chatbots in Real-World Settings: Case Study [13] The AI-enabled system, Doc-torBot, is a health chatbot designed to enhance patientcentred care by providing diagnostic suggestions and collecting feedback, aiming to offer accessible medical consultations and improve user experience by making the chatbot more informative, user-friendly, and trustworthy AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment A Sector-Based Approach to AI ethics: Understanding Ethical Issues of AI-related Incidents within Their Sectoral context [33] The \"AIAAIC repository\" is used to analyse AI-related incidents across various sectors by conducting qualitative content analysis on media reports, helping identify breaches in ethical principles such as accuracy, bias, and privacy, and understanding the specific ethical issues and consequences within each sector Mix roles Unclear Deployment Algorithmic Hiring in Practice: Recruiter and HR Professional's Perspectives on AI Use in Hiring [44] The study explores how AI-enabled hiring software affects HR practices, discussing different types such as candidate recommender guides, task-based, video-based, and gamebased assessments (e.g., HireVue, Hiretual, LinkedIn, HiredScore), and highlights its efficiency in processing diverse candidate data, yet notes industry-specific implementation and concerns over data accuracy and algorithm control, which influences the adoption and impact within organisations AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment FATE in AI: Towards Algorithmic Inclusivity and Accessibility [53] The paper explores AI models in online ad customisation, assessing fairness, accountability, transparency, and ethics (FATE) through user studies and participatory sessions, and proposes community-led data curation for responsible AI development and context-specific recommendations Human-controlled AI Minimal risk Deployment Title (alphabetically) High-level description of the AI-enabled systems or POC AI roles in the use case (See Table 6 for description) Levels of risk associated with use of AI-enabled systems AI lifecycle phases Ground Truth or Dare: Factors Affecting the Creation Of Medical Datasets For Training AI [40] The article does not describe a specific AI-enabled system but provides insights into the preparatory phases of medical dataset creation for AI training, detailing interviews with stakeholders like data scientists and radiologists to investigate factors influencing dataset creation and emphasising responsible data creation approaches in the \"pre-development\" stages of AI applications Mix roles Unclear Pre-development (POC) Human-Centered AI Design in Reality: A Study of Developer Companies' Practices [48] This study explores the application of Human-Centered AI (HCAI) principles in early AI development stages through interviews with practitioners from AI developer companies, uncovering challenges such as detachment from technical development, client-driven user requirements, AI's uncertain nature, and a lack of value-based understanding Mix roles Unclear Development Improving the Accuracy and Transparency of Underwriting with Artificial Intelligence to Transform the Life-Insurance Industry [8] The AI-enabled system in the use case is a mortality model developed by MassMutual that generates a \"life score,\" intended to enhance the accuracy and efficiency of life insurance underwriting by using large datasets and a responsible AI framework to predict mortality risk more effectively, employing the Shapley Additive Explanation (SHAP) framework to increase transparency AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment Integration of the Vision of People with Diabetes into the Development Process to Improve Self-management via Diabetes Apps: Qualitative Interview Study [64] The envisioned AI-enabled system could ideally help patients predict blood glucose levels through algorithms, and embedding an AI into an app could help improve self-management of various daily activities AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment Title (alphabetically) High-level description of the AI-enabled systems or POC AI roles in the use case (See Table 6 for description) Levels of risk associated with use of AI-enabled systems AI lifecycle phases Investigating How Practitioners Use Human-AI Guidelines: A Case Study on the People + AI Guidebook [61] The article examines how industry practitioners use human-AI guidelines in their design practices, revealing their use not only for addressing AI design challenges but also for education, resource development, crossfunctional communication, and team buy-in, while identifying a need for enhanced support in early ideation and problem formulation to better prevent AI product failures and improve guideline effectiveness in early product development stages Mix roles High risk Development Large Language Models for Therapy Recommendations Across 3 Clinical Specialties: Comparative Study [36] The AI-enabled systems in the use case (LLMs like Claude-instant-v1.0, GPT-3.5-Turbo, Command-xlargenightly, and Bloomz) are intended to generate medical therapy recommendations for specialties such as ophthalmology, orthopaedics, and dermatology, aiming to provide accurate, reliable medical advice and improve healthcare efficiency and accessibility AI-assisted decision making High risk Development Lessons Learned from Problem Gambling Classification: Indirect Discrimination and Algorithmic Fairness [46] The AI-enabled system developed by Playtech uses AI to identify online players at risk of problem gambling; designed to be gender-blind to avoid discrimination, the study also explores integrating gender data only during training through separate models for different genders combined into an ensemble, enhancing fairness and accuracy while maintaining privacy AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment One Size Does Not Fit All: Participants' Experiences of the SelfBACK App to Support Self-Management of Low Back Pain-A Qualitative Interview Study [62] The study explores the implementation of the selfBACK app, an AI-driven digital tool for self-managing low back pain (LBP), using interviews and Normalisation Process Theory to understand user engagement and satisfaction, highlighting both the facilitating and impeding factors affecting its use and effectiveness Human controlled AI High risk Deployment 1 3 Title (alphabetically) High-level description of the AI-enabled systems or POC AI roles in the use case (See Table 6 for description) Levels of risk associated with use of AI-enabled systems AI lifecycle phases Open Video Data Sharing in Developmental Science and Clinical Practice [58] This article investigates the use of face-blurring for pseudonymisation in sharing video data in developmental science and clinical settings, emphasising responsible data-sharing practices that maintain participant confidentiality without compromising data utility, demonstrated through a study where face-blurred videos effectively supported General Movement Assessment without reducing accuracy, thus facilitating broader data sharing for scientific and public health benefits Human-controlled AI High risk Pre-development (POC) Participatory Algorithmic Management: Elicitation Methods for Worker Well-Being Models [59] The article examines a participatory method using AI algorithms to model worker well-being, enabling shift workers to build their own models based on work preferences and managerial fairness, demonstrating how it effectively incorporates worker perspectives into algorithmic management practices Human-controlled AI High risk Pre-development (POC) Patchwork: The Hidden, Human Labor of AI Integration within Essential Work [14] The paper analyses the crucial role of frontline workers in essential industries during the COVID-19 pandemic, who perform \"patchwork\" labour to mitigate the discrepancies between the intended and actual outcomes of rapidly implemented AI and automation technologies Human-controlled AI High risk Deployment Public Health Calls for/with AI: An Ethnographic Perspective [47] The article explores the integration of an AI system into India's mCare program to enhance maternal and child health engagement through ethnographic fieldwork, revealing how the AI identifies participants at risk of disengagement, thus optimising resource allocation and enhancing program impact by enabling targeted human interventions Collaborative AI High risk Deployment Title (alphabetically) High-level description of the AI-enabled systems or POC AI roles in the use case (See Table 6 for description) Levels of risk associated with use of AI-enabled systems AI lifecycle phases Questioning the AI: Informing Design Practices for Explainable AI User Experiences [54] This article explores the integration of explainable AI (XAI) into user-centred design within the tech industry by using interviews with 20 UX practitioners (all from IBM), to identify gaps between AI capabilities and user needs, creating a question bank to guide meaningful AI explanations, and stressing the importance of user-focused approaches in industry practices Mix roles Mix of levels Development Rethinking the Role of AI with Physicians in Oncology: Revealing Perspectives from Clinical and Research Workflows [37] The article examines the use of image-based AI systems in oncology to revolutionise cancer care through quantitative analysis of medical images, emphasising the necessity for clinician supervision and discussing the critical attributes of AI, such as explainability and control, within varied clinical and research workflows AI-assisted decision making High risk Unclear Risk Assessment and Classification of Medical Device Software for the Internet of Medical Things: Challenges Arising from Connected, Intelligent Medical Devices [52] The article examines the challenges of evolving risk profiles in Connected, Intelligent Medical Devices (CIMDs) in healthcare, noting significant cybersecurity, data management, and algorithmic integrity issues, and calls for updated risk assessment, classification, and management frameworks to ensure transparency and maintain patient safety and device reliability AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment Stories from the Frontline: Recuperating Essential Worker Accounts of AI Integration [15] The AI-enabled system, developed by Northern Robotics, involves autonomous floor cleaning robots equipped with UV light at an airport, introduced during the COVID-19 pandemic to augment janitorial staff's cleaning routines, but the integration of these robots necessitated careful calibration and coordination by janitorial staff and airport management, underscoring the essential role of human oversight alongside technological advancements Human-controlled AI High risk Deployment 1 3 Title (alphabetically) High-level description of the AI-enabled systems or POC AI roles in the use case (See Table 6 for description) Levels of risk associated with use of AI-enabled systems AI lifecycle phases Supporting Human-AI Collaboration in Auditing LLMs with LLMs [60] AdaTest + + is an AI-enabled system designed for collaborative auditing of large language models (LLMs), enabling users to audit commercial NLP models interactively and manage test suggestions and discovered failures, enhancing the transparency and effectiveness of audits Human-controlled AI High risk Development The Ethical Use of High-Performance Computing and Artificial Intelligence: Fighting COVID-19 at Barcelona Supercomputing Center [41] The intended use of described systems (a combination of high-performance computing and AI technologies) was to support health professionals and researchers in understanding and combating the pandemic, emphasising the ethical, transparent, and fair use of sensitive data in alignment with EU guidelines AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment The Fallacy of AI Functionality [69]The article critiques the pervasive assumption of AI functionality in public discourse and policymaking and emphasises the need for a more critical approach to evaluating AI systems' functionality before deployment, advocating for policy and organisational changes to address flaws and protect communities from the consequences of malfunctioning AI systems Mix roles High risk DeploymentThe Medical Authority of AI: A Study of AI-enabled Consumer-Facing Health Technology [39] The AI-enabled system, Artificial Intelligence-based Symptom Checkers (AISCs), used in consumer health technologies, collects user symptoms to provide medical advice and diagnoses, aiming to redefine traditional medical authority by offering an alternative to physician consultations AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment 1 3 Title (alphabetically) High-level description of the AI-enabled systems or POC AI roles in the use case (See Table 6 for description) Levels of risk associated with use of AI-enabled systems AI lifecycle phases The Need for Knowledge Extraction: Understanding Harmful Gambling Behavior with Neural Networks [35] The article discusses the use of neural networks and the adapted TREPAN knowledge extraction algorithm to predict self-exclusion among gamblers, generating humanreadable decision trees that enhance transparency and interpretability in responsible gambling by facilitating understanding of harmful gambling behaviour and improving decision-making for operators Human-controlled AI Unclear Development Toward Involving End-users in Interactive Human-in-the-loop AI Fairness [43] The article describes a tool designed to allow nontechnical end-users to assess and address fairness issues in AI systems through tools that enable understanding and adjustment of AI decisions, specifically in loan applications, based on explanatory debugging principles and integrating cultural considerations to enhance the inclusivity and effectiveness of AI fairness audits AI-assisted decision making High risk Development Using Model Cards for Ethical Reflection: A Qualitative Exploration [42] The article examines the use of Model Cards, a structured documentation tool for AI developers, to reflect on and document ethical considerations in model development, assessing through qualitative research how this tool influences ethical awareness and transparency during design and development, especially in high-stake scenarios like loan applications and university admissions AI-assisted decision making High risk Pre-development (POC) Values in Emotion Artificial Intelligence Hiring Services: Technosolutions to Organizational Problems [34] This study analyses the use of Emotion Artificial Intelligence (EAI) in hiring, examining how EAI services market their technology as solutions to hiring issues like (in)accuracy, (mis)fit, and (in)authenticity, and highlights concerns over their actual utility and ethical implications, suggesting they may also perpetuate biases and undermine fairness AI-assisted decision making High risk Deployment 1 3 Title (alphabetically) High-level description of the AI-enabled systems or POC AI roles in the use case (See Table 6 for description) Levels of risk associated with use of AI-enabled systems AI lifecycle phases Walking the Walk of AI Ethics: Organizational Challenges and the Individualization of Risk among Ethics Entrepreneurs [66] The article explores the challenges ethics workers face in integrating AI ethics within technology companies, highlighting the individual risks for workers from marginalised backgrounds and the structural and cultural obstacles that hinder ethical practices, with a particular emphasis on how product innovation prioritisation and a lack of institutional support often led to the shortfall of actual ethical implementations Mix roles High risk All phases What Does It Mean to be a Responsible AI Practitioner: An Ontology of Roles and Skills [67] The article investigates the emerging roles and requires skills for responsible AI practitioners by analysing job postings and interviews to create an ontology, detailing the necessary functions, skills, and qualifications for roles like researchers, data scientists, and policy analysts, and underscores the importance of interdisciplinary capabilities and ethical considerations in AI development Mix roles Unclear Unclear Where Responsible AI Meets Reality: Practitioner Perspectives on Enablers for Shifting Organizational Practices [50] The article examines the integration of responsible AI practices within organisations, highlighting the disparity between theoretical frameworks and practical implementation through semi-structured interviews with industry professionals, and maps current and future organisational structures that influence responsible AI initiatives, emphasising the necessity for clear organisational strategies to effectively transition and implement these practices Mix roles Unclear Unclear Who Audits the Auditors?",
